<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Feasibility evaluation of a DOS to SNES port?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12336&amp;p=140539#p140539"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">GradualGames wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />By tile grid, do you mean whatever the SNES's equivalent is of CHR data on the NES? Or do you mean size of a scrollable map?<br /></div><br />I'm talking about the size of the metatile grid on which objects in a scrollable map are placed. For example, <em>Super Mario Bros.</em> uses a grid of 16x16 pixel spaces, <em>Kirby Super Star</em> uses 24x24, and <em>Dr. Mario</em> uses 8x8. Likewise, <em>Chip's Challenge</em> has an obvious grid, as do other PC games like <em>Hocus Pocus</em>, <em>Commander Keen</em> series, <em>Syobon Action</em>, <em>I Wanna Be the Guy</em>, and <em>Warcraft</em>. The grid in <em>Jazz Jackrabbit</em> is a bit more disguised, but it's there. There's even a grid in <em>Starcraft</em>, but it's hard to see outside the map editor. The metatile size on PC will determine part of the port's architecture.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Feb 03, 2015 7:50 pm</p><hr />
